		"description" : [{
				"@" : {
					"type" : "1",
					"xml:lang" : "en"
				},
				"text" : "Expected Outcome: Increased access to quality obstetric and neonatal health service in the districts, particularly among the most vulnerable groups (HIV positive, hard to reach and poorest pregnant women).\r\nRelated indicators are:\r\n- Intrapartum and very early neonatal death rate at Emonc facilities\r\n- Percentage of births assisted by a skilled attendant\r\n- Percentage of HIV infected pregnant women who receive antiretrovirals to reduce the risk of MTCT\r\nExpected Outputs:\r\n- Iringa District Council Designated Hospital carries out quality and comprehensive emergency and obstetric and neonatal care with service available daily on a 24 hours basis\r\n- Six health centers in Iringa District and two in Mufindi District are upgraded to offerbasic Emergency Obstetric and Neonatal Care\r\n- Improved availability of quality health services for HIV positive mothers and exposed newborns at Iringa DC hospital and eight health centers into two districts\r\n- A functional emergency referral system 24 hours a day, seven days a week is available within involved districts referring patients to Iringa DC Hospital\r\n- Forty rural villages in Iringa District and twenty in Mufindi District are reache dby the network of Community Health Workers for community mobilization, awareness creation and behavioral change promotion\r\n- Equity in access to emergency obstetric and newborn care in Iringa DC and Mufindi is improved to through reduction of barries to access\r\nDirect Beneficiaries:\r\n- Women in childberaring age (65640 in Iringa DC and 35992 in two divisions of Mufindi District) and particularly women with complicated deliveries (1300 in IDC and 700 in Mufindi)\r\n- Newborns 8564 in IDC and 4760 in Mufindi District with special attentio to complicated deliveries\r\n- Health staff trained  and re-trained (82)\r\n- Community Health Workers  (102) and CHWs Supervisors (18)\r\n- Number of women groups (20)\r\nIndirect Beneficiaries:\r\n- The total population  of Iringa DC and 2 divisions of Mufindi District (272707 and 128000 respectively). Subgropus: Households of involved villages (25000)\r\n- Staff of the Hcs involved (180 in Iringa, 60 in Mufindi District)\r\n- District Health Authorities: Council Health Management Team members (40), RHC members (10)\r\n"
			}
		],
